<P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#E5E5E6><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub66.ezboard.com/uuhgreebugga.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uhgree Bugga</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>h0x0r!</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>2/19/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>11:55:01 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: The Ashen Order Is Under Attack! Chapter 2</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Overall, good story. You have great potential and I hope you are up for some constructive criticism. This is truly to help you in the future.<br>
<br>
1. Paragraphs - They make your work so much easier to read and help you organize your thought patterns. A well organized story typically gets fleshed out better.<br>
<br>
2. Punctuation - I can never stress this enough. Far too many commas where a sentence should end. What it looks like is a rough draft. That is fine, but you should go back once you've brain dumped everything and make corrections. If you need help with this, ask your English teacher.<br>
<br>
3. Spelling/Word usage - A pet peeve of mine but for good reason. If you want your literary works to be enjoyed 100%, use a spell checker and find out which spelling of a particular word is correct. It takes seconds to find accurate spelling here:<br>
www.m-w.com<br>
Personally, I write in Notepad first. I make corrections and work the story line as I go.<br>
<br>
I realize you are doing this for fun so please feel free to ignore my suggestions. I posted this here because you show good potential and I wish to help. Another option to help improve writing skills is to read existing novels. I would highly suggest R.A. Salvatore's books dealing with dark elves of Menzzoberanzen. The writing style is superb.<br>
<br>
And remember, practice makes perfect. So keep 'em coming.<br>
<br>
/wave<br>
<br>
